## Online Tracking

In recent years, major web browsers have introduced several mitigations to reduce tracking and enhance user privacy. Each browser has taken a unique approach tailored to its ecosystem. Microsoft Edge integrates tools like Tracking Prevention, which blocks known trackers based on three levels of strictness (Basic, Balanced, and Strict), relying on Microsoft's blocklist to limit invasive scripts. Google Chrome, while historically more lenient toward third-party cookies, has begun implementing privacy features like the Privacy Sandbox, which phases out third-party cookies in favor of more privacy-preserving APIs like FLoC (now Topics) and Fenced Frames. Safari has pioneered in this domain with its Intelligent Tracking Prevention (ITP), which uses machine learning to limit cross-site tracking by reducing the ability of third-party cookies to follow users across websites. Meanwhile, Mozilla Firefox employs Enhanced Tracking Protection (ETP), which blocks trackers by default using blocklists from Disconnect.me, and includes features like Total Cookie Protection, preventing cookies from being shared across sites. Each of these browsers demonstrates a commitment to reducing the pervasive tracking that has traditionally compromised user privacy online.

However, tracking still remains pervasive across the web, with a significant percentage of desktop (%) and mobile (%) websites containing at least one third-party tracker. These trackers enable companies to build detailed user profiles based on online behavior, which can be used for personalized advertising, providing insights to website owners, or distinguishing legitimate users from bots. In the following sections, we explore the various techniques trackers use to monitor user activity and examine how they attempt to bypass the privacy protections introduced by modern browsers.

### Stateful tracking

#### Third-party tracking services

One of the most common forms of online tracking is through third-party services, where a website owner typically includes a third-party, cross-site, script that provides site analytics or shows advertisements to visitors. This script can then set a third-party cookie, and log which website the user visited. Whenever the user visits another website that includes the same third-party service, the cookie will be sent along to the tracker, allowing them to re-identify the user and link both website visits to the same profile.
We leverage data from [WhoTracks.Me](http://WhoTracks.Me), a publicly available list that catalogs third-party trackers present across a wide range of websites. By utilizing this resource, we identify the most prevalent trackers on the websites. This helped us assess the dominance of certain tracking companies and better understand the overall landscape of third-party tracking.
Google-owned domains dominate the tracking landscape, with googleapis.com and gstatic appearing on the highest percentage of pages—68% and 61%, respectively. Other prominent trackers include google\_tag and google\_analytics, each seen on over 50% of pages, highlighting the significant reach of Google's tracking services. Additionally, platforms like Facebook and YouTube also play notable roles in third-party tracking, though with lesser coverage compared to Google.
![][image2]

##### Third-Party Cookies

![][image3]

Third-party cookies are the main mechanism used to track the users on the web. Our measurements reveal that Google’s doubleclick.com is the largest source of third-party cookies, with presence on more than a quarter of the crawled web pages. Compared to the 2022 measurements \[INSERT LINK FOR 2022 measurements\], the top sources of third-party cookies have remained largely static, with the notable absence of Facebook, previously the second-largest source of third-party cookies. However, as shown in the next section, we instead see a significant number of cookies set by Facebook in the first-party context.

In order to identify trackers that share cookies across many domains, we also examine the most common names for third-party cookies. We note that the top four cookie names correspond to cookies set by Google’s advertising products and Youtube, as described in their documentation \[INSERT LINK TO [https://business.safety.google/adscookies/](https://business.safety.google/adscookies/)\], and the fifth most-common name corresponds to a cookie set by Cloudflare.
Cloudflare’s cookie, \_\_cf\_bm, is used to “identify and mitigate automated traffic” \[INSERT LINK to https://developers.cloudflare.com/fundamentals/reference/policies-compliances/cloudflare-cookies/\#\_\_cf\_bm-cookie-for-cloudflare-bot-products\]. As this cookie is set on the domains of Cloudflare’s individual customers, it is not captured in a per-domain ranking of cookies.

##### First-Party Cookies

![][image5]

When measuring common first-party cookies, we see extensive evidence of analytics and advertising services setting cookies in the first-party context. The top two cookies, \_ga and \_gid, are both part of Google Analytics. The next cookie, \_fbp, is a tracking cookie set by Facebook. Since 2022, Facebook’s cookie tracking appears to have moved primarily from the third-party context into the first-party context; the default setting for the Meta Pixel now sets first-party cookies \[INSERT LINK to https://www.facebook.com/business/help/471978536642445?id=1205376682832142\]. The majority of the remaining cookies are either additional Google cookies or cookies associated with Sourcebuster, a site analytics plugin. Only two of the top cookie names, PHPSESSID and XSRF-TOKEN, have a clear non-tracking purpose. PHPSESSID is the default cookie name used by the PHP framework to store the user’s session ID, and XSRF-TOKEN is a default name used by the Angular framework.

### Stateless Tracking Technologies

#### Fingerprinting

As browsers continue to expand the restrictions placed on cookies, fingerprinting–a technique that combines data from various browser APIs to develop a unique identifier for a particular user–has become an attractive alternative. Prior studies have found that fingerprinting is now common and is increasing in prevalence. Here, we attempt to determine the most common sources of fingerprinting across the web.

Detecting fingerprinting is difficult, as the APIs used in fingerprinting can also be used for non-tracking purposes. To identify potential sources of fingerprinting, we start by examining the source code of FingerprintJS, a commonly-used fingerprinting library. After compiling a list of APIs used by the library, we search for occurrences of these APIs in each request, and mark any script with 5 or more usages as a potential fingerprinting script. Finally, we rank the scripts by the number of pages on which they are loaded.

![][image6]

Through this, we find a mixture of scripts that are primarily used for tracking, and scripts that also have a non-tracking purpose. Recaptcha, the most common script, is known to use fingerprinting to separate humans from bots. Google Ads and Yandex Metrika are also primarily tracking scripts. However, other scripts, such as the Google Maps API and Youtube embed API, also have a non-tracking purpose, and so their usage of these APIs may have purposes other than fingerprinting. Further manual analysis is required to confirm whether these scripts are actually performing fingerprinting.

### Advanced Evasion Techniques

#### CNAME tracking

Blocklist-based tracking protections, such as ad blockers, often block third-party requests to trackers based on the domain of the request. In order to circumvent existing tracker-blocking tools, some trackers rely on an alternative tracking technique called CNAME cloaking or CNAME tracking. When using this method, trackers work together with websites and allocate a first-party subdomain of the website for tracking, which is connected to the actual third-party trackers  by using a CNAME-record at the DNS level. Therefore, the first-party request will not be blocked by an adblocker and all cookies are set in a first-party context.
For example, the website *exampleherbalife.com* would use a subdomain *subdomainsmetrics.exampleherbalife.com* which has a CNAME record pointing to *exampleherbalife.trackeromtrdc.comnect*, which is a tracking domain belonging to Adobe and would have been blocked by blocklist-based tracking protections.

To report on CNAME tracking, we base our analysis on DNS data. More specifically, we retain requests which use a CNAME pointing at a different eTLD+1 than the website’s eTLD+1. Hosting services such as CDNs also utilize CNAME-records to connect customer websites with their servers. Nonetheless, hosting services retain tracking capabilities and provide mixed-purpose services. For our analysis however, we only consider domains used primarily for tracking or advertising. We achieve this by comparing the resulting domains with WhoTracksMe’s list of trackers and AdGuard’s CNAME trackers lists \[[https://github.com/AdguardTeam/cname-trackers](https://github.com/AdguardTeam/cname-trackers)\].

![][image7]

The graph shows the top 10 most widely-used CNAME domains. We only include domains which were categorized as used for analytics and/or advertising by WhoTracksMe.
We find that wordpress, which is used to provide insights about the usage of websites, is the most prevalent CNAME tracker. Following, we find omtrdc.net and 2o7.net, which are both operated by Adobe Experience Cloud.

We find a very similar distribution for the number eTLDs+1 used in CNAME subdomains. This observation is consistent with the correlation between the number of websites that use CNAME-based tracking and the number of CNAME subdomains, given that each website is assigned one CNAME subdomain per tracker in the typical CNAME scenario. In some cases however, the origin of the request can also be third-party. For example, Adobe includes a CNAME from *smetrics.ford.com* to *ford.com.ssl.sc.omtrdc.net* on multiple websites.
In our analysis, we find that *salesforce.com* uses the highest number of different CNAME domains. Most CNAME trackers use both first-party and third-party CNAME domains. For instance, third-party requests to *bpd.my.salesforce-sites.com* and *loreal-consumer1.secure.force.com* point to a domain owned by *salesforce.com*, while other websites might include a first-party request such as *kundportal.lidl.se* pointing to *ia4.edge2.salesforce.com.*
The graph shows only the 10 most popular CNAME trackers. In total we found 13 CNAME trackers classified as used for advertising or analytics by WhoTracksMe and being present on at least 100 websites. Yootta, which is an analytics company, is prevalent on sites such as *skiphop.com* by including a unique CNAME subdomain to *15d78b804a3e01363612026173a6dedd.yottaa.net.*

In summary, CNAMEs are increasingly being used for tracking in practice. Not only do they use first-party subdomains, but even when cloaking the tracking domain under a different third-party domain, the trackers can still circumvent blocklists.

**CNAME mitigating.** Browser vendors and privacy-enhancing browser extensions propose mechanisms to curb CNAME tracking. For example, Brave browser, relies on DNS resolution to uncover CNAME domains and then blocks them. In the case of Safari, it
caps the lifetime of cookies (i.e., through Safari ITP).

#### Bounce tracking

Most browsers now either block third-party cookies (https://webkit.org/tracking-prevention/) or partition them by first-party (https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Privacy/Third-party\_cookies), which makes them inaccessible across sites. Bounce tracking is a bypass that allows trackers to read/write their cookies across sites, rendering third-party cookie blocking ineffective (https://github.com/privacycg/nav-tracking-mitigations/blob/main/bounce-tracking-explainer.md).

Bounce tracking is a technique to bypass third-party cookie restrictions in Safari. Specifically, Safari restricts a domain from setting cookies if it has not been visited as a full-fledged website.
At a high level, bounce tracking works by momentarily tricking or forcing the browser to visit a domain as a full-fledged website, which provides the domain an opportunity to seed its cookies as a first-party, which it can later access when it is loaded as a third-party. After the cookie is set, the user is either redirected back to the original website, or to the website that they are navigating to. With our analysis, we only report on the prior scenario.

This method is often also used for advertising campaign measurements in addition to being used for cross-site tracking purposes. We identify bounce tracking domains by examining whether the webpage instantaneously redirect the user to a page of a third-party tracker, that sets a first-party cookie, before redirecting the user back to the original page.

![][image8]
The graph shows the number of websites that include the most widely-used bounce tracking hostnames. Among the top bounce tracking domains are *demon.indapass.hu* with a prevalence on 422 websites and *medium.com* on 364 websites*.*

We note that our results should be considered as upper-bound for bounce tracking. Not all of the domains that we found are actually exhibiting privacy-intrusive behavior. One valid use case for redirecting the user to a domain, setting a cookie and bouncing back is federated authentication. In the case of OAuth for instance, it is common to lead the user to an authorization endpoint. Some of the domains in our analysis are possibly related to SSO for this reason (e.g., *accounts.outsideonline.com*).
A limitation to using bounce tracking is that first-party cookies do not allow cross-site tracking of users. Some browsers, such as Brave, actively block bounce tracking.

### Browser policies to improve privacy

It is a common practice for websites to include content from third-party services, such as the advertising and social media platforms. Unfortunately, third-party services cannot be implicitly trusted, as more often than not, they directly harm user privacy, e.g., third-party tracking services. Recently, web standards bodies and browser vendors have tried to step in and provide many controls to website developers that they can use to mitigate privacy threats posed by third-party services. We analyze the prevalence of such prominent browser-provided controls.

#### User-Agent Client Hints

In an effort to minimize the amount of information exposeddisclosed about the browsing environment, particularly through viaregarding the User-Agent string, the User-Agent Client Hints mechanism was has been introduced by browsers and standards bodies.

The key idea is that the wWebsites that want to access certain information about the users’ browsing environment (browser version, operating system, screen resolution, etc.) have to set a header (Accept-CH) in the first response.
![][image9]
We measure the prevalence of Accept-CH header and note that it is deployed by 16.18% of the top-1K and 5.22% of the top-10K websites. When we look at the adoption of sites that respond with the Accept-CH header in comparison with the results from 2022 ([https://almanac.httparchive.org/en/2022/privacy\#user-agent-client-hints](https://almanac.httparchive.org/en/2022/privacy#user-agent-client-hints)) (top 1K: 9.53%, top 10K: 3.14%), we see an increase in adoption by 6.65% for the 1K popular sites.

We surmise that this increase in adoption is related to the fact that Chromium has been reducing the information that is shared in the User-Agent string (through the User-Agent Reduction plan) ([https://www.chromium.org/updates/ua-reduction/](https://www.chromium.org/updates/ua-reduction/)).

For all websites, Accept-CH is deployed in 0.44% and 0.49% of all the crawled websites for desktop and mobile, respectively.
When we look at the adoption of sites that respond with the Accept-CH header in comparison with the results from 2022 (top 1Kk: 9.53%, top 10Kk: 3.14%) and the results from 2021  (top 1Kk: 3.56%, top 10Kk: 1.44%), we see a significant increase in adoption, more than 0.5 for the most 1K popular sites.

Our analysis indicates that websites utilizing User-Agent Client Hints tend to request access to a relatively large number of properties, thereby diminishing the intended benefits of initiatives such as User-Agent Reduction. It remains to be seen how, or if, browsers will implement further restrictions on the collection of extensive information about the user's browsing environment in the near future.

#### Referrer Policy

By default, most user agents include a Referer header, which discloses to third parties the website—or even the specific page—from which a request originated. This occurs for any resource embedded within a webpage, as well as for requests triggered by a user clicking on a link. Consequently, third parties may gain insight into which website or page a particular user was visiting, leading to potential privacy concerns.

![][image10]

By making use of the Referrer Policy (https://developer.mozilla.org/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Referrer-Policy), websites can limit the instances in which the Referrer header is included in requests and thus improve user privacy.

Referrer policy can be included both at the document-level and also at the request-level. We find that referrer policy is deployed on 33.87% of the desktop web pages and 32% of the mobile web pages, overall. On 21.82% of such pages, refer policy is deployed at the request-level with the \`ref=noreferer\` HTML tag, and in 11.31% of the instances, the referrer policy is deployed at the document level.

BHowever, by employing the Referrer Policy, websites can control when the Referer header is included in requests, thereby enhancing user privacy. We note that 33.87% of the desktop web pages and 32% of the mobile web pages include referrer policy.
 include referrer policy header in HTTP headers.

We find that 11 % of the desktop sites (1% less than 2022\)  and 10 % of the mobile sites (equal to 2022\) set such a document-wide policy, mostly via an HTTP response header.
![][image11]
While referrer policy allows to mitigate some tracking, not all of its options have the same effect. Thus we next measure the deployment of individual referrer policy options.

Our analysis reveals that the \`strict-origin-when-cross-origin\` is the most commonly used option of the Referrer Policy, with a deployment on 8% of the crawled web pages. We also note that its deployment has increased by nearly 3X as compared to 2022 ([https://almanac.httparchive.org/en/2022/privacy\#user-agent-client-hints](https://almanac.httparchive.org/en/2022/privacy#user-agent-client-hints)) when it was deployed on only 2.68% of the crawled web pages.

\`strict-origin-when-cross-origin\` is also the default option (i.e., if no policy is specified) and only shares the full url in the \`referer\` header to the same-origin requests. For cross-origin requests, the path and the query string parameters are stripped out.

The next most commonly deployed option is \`no-referrer-when-downgrade\`, which does not include the Referer header on downgrade requests, that is, HTTP requests initiated on an HTTPS-enabled page. Unfortunately, this still leaks the page that the user is visiting in most scenarios—in HTTPS-enabled requests

Our analysis reveals that the most common application of the Referrer Policy is to exclude the \`Referer\` header on downgrade requests—specifically, when HTTP requests are made from an HTTPS-enabled page.

However, in the majority of cases, this still exposes the page a user is visiting in HTTPS-enabled requests. Notably, 8% of desktop sites and 7% of mobile sites now utilize the \`strict-origin-when-cross-origin\` policy to conceal the specific page a user is visiting. This policy, which has become the default in most browsers when no explicit policy is set, is more prevalent than \`no-referrer-when-downgrade\`, and both have seen an increase in adoption since 2022\.

#### Related Privacy-related Origins Trials

Origin trials allow website developers to test new features released by web browsers, e.g., browser APIs. Once website developers register in origin trials, the new browser features are made available to all their users. Since web browsers are increasingly deploying privacy-enhancing features, such as eliminating third-party cookies, we next analyze whether website developers are participating in privacy-related origin trials to assess their readiness for the upcoming privacy-enhancing features in browsers.

Related Origin Trials provide a framework for testing multiple interrelated experimental web platform features simultaneously. Unlike individual Origin Trials, which focus on isolated features, Related Origin Trials allow developers to evaluate how a set of connected APIs or functionalities interact in practice. This approach offers a more comprehensive understanding of the combined use of features, enabling developers to assess their collective performance, compatibility, and impact on the user experience. By facilitating the testing of feature ecosystems, Related Origin Trials contribute to more efficient development processes and provide valuable feedback to browser vendors regarding the readiness and practical application of new web technologies.

### Privacy Sandbox Proposals

**Overview.** Privacy Sandbox, introduced by Google in 2019, contains several proposals that are aimed at curbing privacy-invasive practices on the web by aiming to strike a balance between user privacy and the continued viability of online advertising, which supports free content and services on the web. Among  privacy sandbox proposals, Protected Audience, Topics, and Attribution Reporting have garnered significant attention because of their implications on interest-based ad auctions, targeted advertising and privacy-preserving conversion tracking, respectively. In this section, we measure the adoption of these proposals to assess the readiness of websites and ad-tech (e.g., advertising platforms, tracking entities), in incorporating these proposals.

We first provide the prevalence of these APIs. We note that Protected Audience API (previously known as FLEDGE), Topics API, and Attribution Reporting API have the highest adoption in terms of the number of publishers using these APIs. These are respectively used by 439 (43.9%), 245 (24.5%), and 203 (20.3%) of top-1K) websites. Amongst top-10M websites, the adoption scales to 39.6%, 5.2%, and 15.4% publishers, respectively.

**Protected Audience API adoption.** Protected Audience API enables on-device auctions by the browser, to choose relevant ads from websites the user has previously visited. It eliminates the need for privacy-invasive data collection and pervasive tracking practices that are otherwise employed for remarketing and targeted advertising. This ensures that advertisers can serve relevant ads without needing to track users across sites. Amongst different method calls available for the **Protected Audience API,** we note that navigator.joinAdInterestGroup() is used the most by third-party services – 22K third-parties across 39% of top-10M websites. This API provides an ability to a third-party service to direct the browser to add an interest group to the browser's membership list for the visiting user. Recent research has discovered various privacy flaws with respect to the Protected Audience API \[CITE\]. For example, third-party trackers can potentially link the interest groups of the users to an actual user using side-channels and track them across sites. Possibility of colluding entities further alleviate the associated privacy risks.

**Topics API adoption.** Google’s Topics proposal works by assigning a small set of high-level topics to a user based on their recent browsing activity, such as "sports" or "technology". These topics are stored locally on the user's devices and shared with websites and advertisers to serve relevant ads. Users also have the ability to see and control the topics that are shared with advertisers. Since this API can be deployed both through the HTTP headers and JavaScript, we measure the adoption of **Topics API** across both of these axes. We observe Javascript-based usage (i.e., document.browsingTopics()) (5.2% publishers) to be more widely adopted than header-based usage (i.e., sec-browsing-topics) of Topics (2.5% publishers). Surprisingly, we also note that the **FLoC** API (Federated Learning of Cohorts) – a precursor proposal to Topics API, despite being deprecated due to several privacy issues, is still used by  \~10% of publishers that use Topics API. While Topics API adoption improves the status quo, prior research has shown that monitoring the topics returned by the user’s browser over a period of time can aid in reidentification of users \[CITE\].
![][image14]
![][image15]
**Attribution Reporting API** **(ARA) adoption.** ARA introduces a privacy-preserving mechanism for measuring ad conversions in Google Chrome. Its purpose is to enable attribution measurement by providing a capability to (publishers and advertising platforms) register attribution source and trigger on publisher and advertiser websites, respectively. Chrome records every conversion, and generates a differentially private report that is sent to authorized sources with a delay, preventing cross-site linking of the users. This mechanism works through the use of specific HTTP headers:

1. **`attribution-reporting-eligible`**: This header signals that a particular request’s response is eligible for attribution reporting.
2. **`attribution-reporting-register-source`**: Used to register attribution sources when displaying an advertiser’s ad on publishers.
3. **`attribution-reporting-register-trigger`**: Used on the advertiser's website to register triggers that measure conversions when users interact with ads.

From our analysis, we observe that twice as many third parties are registering triggers compared to those registering sources. This trend indicates a higher focus on measuring conversions as compared to tracking the initial ad display events.

![][image16]
Since most of the popular browsers are competing with each other in the space of privacy preserving attribution with proposals like ARA for Chrome \[CITE\], PCM for Safari \[CITE\], and IPA by Mozilla and Meta \[CITE\], we analyze ARA in more detail. We look at registrations of advertising destinations on different websites. We observe that 81 distinct advertisers are using ARA to register themselves using attribution-reporting-register-trigger header on 49 distinct publishers on the top-1K websites. In total, we observe 8.7K (23.5K) distinct advertisers have adopted ARA across 28.3K (123.3K) publishers in top 1M (top 10M) websites. This shows that not many publishers have adopted ARA as compared to the advertiser adoption – preparing themselves for the post-cookie world where they will need to rely on ARA to attribute user conversions to ad clicks.
![][image17]

The **Related Websites Set** under the Privacy Sandbox proposal allows related publishers to declare themselves in order for the browser to remember user preferences across those related sites even in the absence of third-party cookies. This can result in data sharing and user profiling across multiple sites, enabling cross-site tracking without the user’s knowledge of which websites could be related. The data reveals that 50 distinct publishers (5%) utilize related websites set amongst the top-1K publishers. This further increases within the higher rank groups up to 388.5K (i.e., 3.8%) amongst top-10K publishers, suggesting the scale of these publishers that can link the user across all of their declared related websites.

### Law and Policy

With increasing scrutiny against online tracking, there have been numerous new laws and regulations passed to make online advertisers and trackers more accountable. In this section we look at the impact these regulations have had on privacy.

#### Cookie Consent Dialogs

With the introduction of privacy regulations like the GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation) in the European Union, websites are now required to obtain explicit user consent forbefore collecting, or storing, and processing user data, e.g., collection and usage of third-party tracking cookies obtained through cookies. This has led to the widespread use of cookie consent dialogs, which notify users about the data collection practices and allow them to accept, reject, or customize their consent.
These consent dialogs have become a ubiquitous feature across the web, but their effectiveness in truly protecting user privacy is debated. Many websites use “dark patterns” to nudge users into accepting tracking, while others present complex options that can overwhelm non-technical users.

#### IAB Consent Dialog

The IAB (Interactive Advertising Bureau) Europe introduced the Transparency and Consent Framework (TCF) to standardize the process of obtaining consent for targeted advertising. The IAB consent dialog is used by many websites and ad tech companies to comply with GDPR and other privacy laws while continuing to serve personalized ads.

The framework is designed to provide transparency into how user data is processed and to give users the ability to grant or withhold consent for different purposes, such as personalized ads, analytics, or content delivery.

![][image19]
![][image20]
![][image21]

#### DNT (Do not Track)

Do Not Track (DNT) was a browser-based privacy initiative introduced in the early 2010s. It allowed users to set a browser preference indicating that they did not wish to be tracked by websites. However, DNT failed to gain widespread adoption, largely because it was voluntary and lacked enforcement mechanisms.

While DNT was a pioneering idea in user privacy, it ultimately became obsolete as major advertisers and trackers chose to ignore DNT requests, and it was not enshrined in any legal frameworks. Instead, privacy regulations like GDPR and technologies like GPC (Global Privacy Control) have taken up the mantle. However, our analysis shows that even though it has been replaced by GPC, 13.7% of desktop websites, and 12.77% of mobile websites still support a DNT signal. It’s crucial to point out here that while these sites check for the DNT signal, how well these sites adhere to and comply with the signal is unclear.

#### GPC (Global Privacy Control)

Global Privacy Control (GPC) is a more recent initiative designed to give users a simple, browser-based mechanism to communicate their privacy preferences to websites, similar to DNT. However, unlike DNT, GPC is backed by legal regulations like the CCPA (California Consumer Privacy Act).

GPC allows users to signal that they do not want their data to be sold or shared with third parties, and companies are legally obligated to respect this signal under certain laws. Major browsers and privacy-focused extensions support GPC, and it is gaining traction as a more effective tool for user privacy.

Analysis shows that 55.84% of desktop sites and 54.9% of mobile sites consume the GPC signal through JavaScript, which is significantly higher than the DNT signal. Another optional requirement of GPC is a well-known URL which resides at the /.well-known/gpc.json endpoint (relative to the website’s origin server URL). This resource is meant to indicate that the website abides by GPC requests. While lack of this resource does not mean that the website does not respect GPC, it does complicate tracking compliance, across a large number of sites, a difficult chore. Only 0.27% of mobile sites and 0.26% of desktop sites have an accessible well-known endpoint.
![][image22]

#### CCPA (California Consumer Privacy Act)

The CCPA, enacted in 2018, is one of the most significant privacy laws passed in the United States. It grants California residents rights over their personal data, including the right to know what data is being collected, the right to request deletion of their data, and the right to opt out of the sale of their data.

CCPA has had a profound impact on the web, as companies across the globe must comply if they collect or process data from California residents. This has led to the introduction of “Do Not Sell My Info” links on many websites and increased awareness around data privacy in the U.S.
![][image23]
![][image24]

##### CCPA

In 2020, the California Consumer Privacy Act came into effect. Under the law, any business that does business in California and meets certain size thresholds must provide a way for users to opt-out of the selling or sharing of their personal information. To comply with the law, the California Attorney General’s office recommends placing a link on the business’ homepage with the text “Do Not Sell My Personal Information” and a standardized icon. Building on prior work that identified a common set of CCPA link phrases, we conducted an analysis of the prevalence of these links across sites according to their popularity level.

![][image25]

Large sites (those that have a lower rank index) are more likely to have a CCPA link, either because they are more likely to meet the thresholds to be covered under the CCPA, or simply because they are more aware of the requirements. However, the rate of links among the top 1000 websites is still quite low. While it is impossible to know how many of these sites meet the requirements to be covered under the CCPA, it is likely that they all at least meet the revenue threshold, so unless they take steps to actively block California users, they would appear to be covered.

One limitation of our crawl is that it is geographically distributed, and as such we cannot accurately account for websites that dynamically show a CCPA link only to visitors in California. Therefore, our results likely underestimate the prevalence of these links. A prior study found that as of 2022, 17% of CCPA links were dynamically hidden; this would imply that the rate of compliance among the top 1000 sites is still less than 10%.

Finally, we examine which phrasing is most commonly used in CCPA links. The majority of sites use variants of the phrase required by the law, “do not sell my personal information”. However, a significant number of sites also contain links titled “your privacy choices”, whose implication is less clear. This may make it more difficult for users to opt-out on these sites.

![][image26]

### Advertiser Controls

![][image27]

**Overview.** Online programmatic advertising involves a complicated supply chain where ad slots (i.e., inventory) exposed by publishers could be sold (and resold) by multiple intermediary entities through real-time auctions before end buyers (i.e., advertisers) actually end up bidding on it and displaying their ad. To improve the transparency and security against the prevalent fraud in the ecosystem, Interactive Advertising Bureau (IAB) (an advertising consortium) introduced *ads.txt* and *sellers.json* standards.

**Purpose of advertising standards.** ads.txt (maintained by publisher) lists digital sellers (i.e., ad exchanges, ad networks, or SSPs) that have been authorized by the publisher to sell its ad inventory. Each of these sellers in turn maintains a JSON file declaring their relationship with publishers and other sellers. This allows end buyers to use these files in real-time to verify the identity of sellers by checking if the seller (with the mentioned seller ID in the bid request) auctioning the ad inventory is authorized to do so for the listed publisher (with the given publisher ID) or not. Such validation prevents advertisers from buying fraudulent/misrepresented supply in different scenarios (as described in detail in prior research \[CITE\]).

**ads.txt account distribution.** ads.txt allows a seller to either directly sell its inventory on its behalf or resell it. More resellers in an ads.txt suggests higher indirect selling of ad inventory which can result in longer supply chains – and longer supply chains increase risk of misrepresentations. We plot the distribution of ads.txt seller accounts in the figure below. It can be observed that \~90% publishers avoid reseller dependence and sell their supply directly to the advertisers, reducing possibility of fraud. 60-70% publishers have less than 50 direct accounts. Only \~1% publishers engage in unconventional and potentially specious practices of listing more than 300 direct and/or reseller accounts. Moreover, publishers with a higher number of seller accounts are observed to list a significantly larger number of reseller accounts than the direct accounts in their ads.txt files. This means that they are allowing a large number of intermediary sellers to resell their inventory before it is bought by the advertiser – this could further increase the chances of fraud with more entities being involved in the supply chain. Overall, although the data suggests that only \~1% publishers participate in such practices, these 1% publishers can potentially deplete significant revenue from advertisers by deceiving them into buying inventory on their website.
![][image28]

**ads.txt lines distribution.** As seen in the figure below, the number of lines in the .TXT file is naturally proportional to the number of listed seller accounts. 90% of publishers have less than 10 lines in their ads.txt, leaving only 1% of all publishers that have more than 700 lines worth of ads.txt. A similar trend can also be observed for the mobile publishers (i.e., mobile apps) that need to maintain an app-ads.txt instead of ads.txt file. In addition to the aforementioned explanations, another reason for including a large number of sellers in the ads.txt file (or in other words maintaining a longer .TXT file) is to boost self-reputation by showing that a given publisher is working with multiple sellers.
![][image29]

**ads.txt variables.** Observing the usage of common ads.txt variables suggest:

* The highest adoption of *ownerdomain* (85% of all publishers) – representing declaration of the parent of the current publisher that possesses the ownership of the publisher.
* The programmatic advertising for the publisher is sometimes managed by a separate entity called *managerdomain* – that is observed to be the second most adopted variable (47% of all publishers).

These variables further enhance transparency into ownership and management of the publisher that can aid advertisers in making correct decisions about bidding on an inventory. For example, let’s say in the past, an advertiser has seen low ROI (or conversion rate) or fraudulent impressions when they bid on any inventory from seller.com. Now, if they obtain a bid request from a publisher example.com that is managed by seller.com, then the advertiser can make a more informed decision to not bid on the inventory because of its past experience with seller.com. Without such transparency variables, advertisers would have ended up bidding on the inventory, resulting in a further loss. ![][image30]
**ads.txt sellers.** As expected, Google is listed as a direct seller by 70% of publishers. All of the other sellers have relatively lower publisher coverage as compared to Google. Other popular top direct sellers include popular supply-side platforms and ad-exchanges such as Pubmatic, Appnexus, Amazon, Criteo, etc. With a high percentage of integration on different publishers, these sellers have potential to track and target users across a significant portion of the web. This indirectly also shows the market share of these players that predominantly control the most advertising share.
![][image31]
